# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 2016-afl-women-s-draft
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:2016-afl-women-s-draft/2015-afl-women-s-draft] The **2015 AFL women's draft** was an opportunity for Melbourne and the Western Bulldogs to select players for the Hampson-Hardeman Cup.
[src:2016-afl-women-s-draft/2015-afl-women-s-draft] It consisted of a draft before the first match, held on 20 April and including 34 picks, and a mini-draft before the second match, held on 22 July and including 10 picks.
[src:2016-afl-women-s-draft/2015-afl-women-s-draft] Before the first match, teams were permitted to retain six players from their 2013 squads, and completed their lists through the draft.
[src:2016-afl-women-s-draft/2015-afl-women-s-draft] Coastal Titans ruck Emma King was selected by the Bulldogs with the first pick.
[src:2016-afl-women-s-draft/2015-afl-women-s-draft] Before the first match, six players were selected to be retained by each team, barring unavailability.
[src:2016-afl-women-s-draft/2016-afl-draft] The **2016 AFL draft** consisted of the various periods where the 18 clubs in the Australian Football League (AFL) could trade and recruit players following the completion of the 2016 AFL season.
[src:2016-afl-women-s-draft/2016-afl-draft] Additions to each club's playing list are not allowed at any other time during the year.
[src:2016-afl-women-s-draft/2016-afl-draft] The Brisbane Lions received a priority pick at the end of the first round (pick 19) after a request by the club to the AFL commission was accepted.
[src:2016-afl-women-s-draft/2016-afl-draft] It was the first time a priority pick was given to a club since the rules regarding priority selections were changed in 2012.
[src:2016-afl-women-s-draft/2016-afl-draft] This pick was later on-traded to Port Adelaide as part of the Pearce Hanley trade to Gold Coast, before the Sydney Swans ended up with it by the trade deadline.
[src:2016-afl-women-s-draft/2016-afl-draft] A change was made to the rules concerning academy and father-son selections which allowed clubs to begin the draft with only as many draft picks as it had empty positions on its playing list.
[src:2016-afl-women-s-draft/2016-afl-draft] This was intended to end the practice which had taken place the previous year in which clubs with academies had traded down the draft order to accumulate a large number of mid- and low-range draft picks specifically to use on academy bids.
[src:2016-afl-women-s-draft/2016-afl-draft] Clubs were able to promote any player who was listed on their rookie list in 2016 to their 2017 primary playing list prior to the draft.
[src:2016-afl-women-s-draft/2016-afl-draft] During the trade period, clubs could nominate category B rookies to join their club.
[src:2016-afl-women-s-draft/2016-afl-women-s-draft] The **2016 AFL Women's draft** consisted of the various periods when the eight clubs in the AFL Women's competition recruited players prior to the competition's inaugural season in 2017.
[src:2016-afl-women-s-draft/2016-afl-women-s-draft] Draftees and signings over the period were required to have a minimum age qualification of 18.
[src:2016-afl-women-s-draft/2016-afl-women-s-draft] Prior to the draft itself each club was allowed to sign two marquee players from any state across the country at an increased salary.
[src:2016-afl-women-s-draft/2016-afl-women-s-draft] In addition, they were permitted to sign a number of priority players with existing connections to the club, and up to two rookie players who had not played competitive Australian rules football within the previous three years.
[src:2016-afl-women-s-draft/2016-afl-women-s-draft] All remaining players entered the draft and became eligible to be selected by any team based in their nominated state-based zone.
[src:2016-afl-women-s-draft/2016-afl-women-s-draft] On 27 July 2016, each of the competition's eight teams announced their two marquee player signings allowed prior to the October draft.
[src:2016-afl-women-s-draft/2016-afl-women-s-draft] Under the priority selection rules, Carlton, Collingwood, Melbourne, the Western Bulldogs and Fremantle were allowed one player, Adelaide and Brisbane were allowed two players, and Greater Western Sydney was allowed four.
[src:2016-afl-women-s-draft/2016-afl-women-s-draft] Due to injuries to their marquee players, Fremantle and Greater Western Sydney were permitted an additional priority pick, allowing for two and five in total, respectively.
[src:2016-afl-women-s-draft/2016-afl-women-s-draft] A state based draft was held on 12 October 2016.
[src:2016-afl-women-s-draft/2016-afl-women-s-draft] The draft order was determined by random draw on 29 September.
[src:2016-afl-women-s-draft/2016-afl-women-s-draft] The draft operated in snake formation with the club holding the first selection of the first round also holding the last selection of the second round and so on and so forth.
[src:2016-afl-women-s-draft/2016-afl-women-s-draft] Each team had until 31 October 2016 to sign further undrafted/free-agent players to complete their list of 25 senior listed players.
[src:2016-afl-women-s-draft/2017-afl-women-s-all-australian-team] The **2017 AFL Women's All-Australian team** represents the best-performed players of the 2017 AFL Women's season.
[src:2016-afl-women-s-draft/2017-afl-women-s-all-australian-team] It was announced on 28 March 2017 as a complete women's Australian rules football team of 22 players, the first and only time that this happened before teams in the AFL Women's were reduced to 21 players in 2018.
[src:2016-afl-women-s-draft/2017-afl-women-s-all-australian-team] The team is honorary and does not play any games.
[src:2016-afl-women-s-draft/2017-afl-women-s-all-australian-team] The selection panel for the 2017 AFL Women's All-Australian team consisted of Simon Lethlean, Mark Evans, Josh Vanderloo, Jennie Loughnan, Kevin Sheehan, Peta Searle, Darren Flanigan, Kelli Underwood, Ros Lanigan and Shelley Ware.
[src:2016-afl-women-s-draft/2017-afl-women-s-all-australian-team] The initial 40-woman All-Australian squad was announced on 23 March.
[src:2016-afl-women-s-draft/2017-afl-women-s-all-australian-team] Minor premiers Brisbane had the most players selected in the initial squad with nine, with players from grand finalists Adelaide and Brisbane making up more than one-third of the squad.
[src:2016-afl-women-s-draft/2017-afl-women-s-all-australian-team] The final team was announced on 28 March.
[src:2016-afl-women-s-draft/2017-afl-women-s-all-australian-team] Grand finalists Adelaide and Brisbane had the most representatives with five each, and every team had at least one representative.
[src:2016-afl-women-s-draft/2017-afl-women-s-all-australian-team] Melbourne captain Daisy Pearce was announced as the All-Australian captain and Adelaide co-captain Erin Phillips was announced as the vice-captain.
[src:2016-afl-women-s-draft/2017-afl-women-s-all-australian-team] Note: the position of coach in the AFL Women's All-Australian team is traditionally awarded to the coach of the premiership-winning team.
[src:2016-afl-women-s-draft/2017-afl-women-s-best-and-fairest] The **2017 AFL Women's best and fairest** was the first year the award was presented to the player adjudged the best and fairest player during the AFL Women's (AFLW) home-and-away season.
[src:2016-afl-women-s-draft/2017-afl-women-s-best-and-fairest] Erin Phillips of the Adelaide Football Club won the award with 14 votes.
[src:2016-afl-women-s-draft/2017-afl-women-s-best-and-fairest] The three field umpires (the umpires who control the flow of the game, as opposed to goal or boundary umpires) confer after each match and award three votes, two votes and one vote to the players they regard as the best, second-best and third-best in the match, respectively.
[src:2016-afl-women-s-draft/2017-afl-women-s-best-and-fairest] The votes are kept secret until the awards night, and are read and tallied on the evening.
[src:2016-afl-women-s-draft/2017-afl-women-s-best-and-fairest] The winner of the 2017 AFL Women's best and fairest was Erin Phillips, receiving 14 votes to win the inaugural award.
[src:2016-afl-women-s-draft/2017-afl-women-s-draft] The **2017 AFL Women's draft** consisted of the various periods when the eight clubs in the AFL Women's competition could recruit players prior to the competition's 2018 season.
[src:2016-afl-women-s-draft/2017-afl-women-s-draft] As the previous season's player contracts were all capped at one-year deals, all existing AFLW players must be re-signed prior to the 2018 season.
[src:2016-afl-women-s-draft/2017-afl-women-s-draft] Entering the second season of the competition, clubs will have larger list sizes, with 27 senior listed players (up from 25), and three rookie listed players (up from two).
[src:2016-afl-women-s-draft/2017-afl-women-s-draft] Beginning 1 May, clubs were given an 18-day window to re-sign players on their lists from the previous season, with teams being required to retain between 15 and 22 players during that period.
[src:2016-afl-women-s-draft/2017-afl-women-s-draft] There was also a window for teams to trade players and draft picks in a trade period that started on 15 May 2017, and continued for 12 days.
[src:2016-afl-women-s-draft/2017-afl-women-s-draft] Players were eligible to seek a trade should they receive a contract offer from a rival club at a pay scale level above their previous years' salary.
[src:2016-afl-women-s-draft/2017-afl-women-s-draft] Players could also reject any offer from their existing club lower rate than in 2017, and become restricted free agents permitted to sign with another club at or above their previous salary.
[src:2016-afl-women-s-draft/2017-afl-women-s-draft] Players who do not receive offers from their 2017 club were free to sign with any club during the four-day free agency period starting 29 May 2017 or to nominate for the 2017 draft.
[src:2016-afl-women-s-draft/2017-afl-women-s-draft] A four-day free agency period was held from 29 May for clubs to secure non-signed players from other clubs.
[src:2016-afl-women-s-draft/2017-afl-women-s-draft] A second free agency period opened at the conclusion of the draft, allowing undrafted players to be signed.
[src:2016-afl-women-s-draft/2017-afl-women-s-draft] This period closed on 19 October, the day after the draft.
[src:2016-afl-women-s-draft/2017-afl-women-s-draft] AFLW players salaries are managed and paid in full by the AFL on behalf of the clubs.
[src:2016-afl-women-s-draft/2017-afl-women-s-draft] It is expected that these salaries will be renegotiated and increased, as the time commitment of players was found to be greater than expected during the 2017 season.
[src:2016-afl-women-s-draft/2017-afl-women-s-draft] In addition, players are provided with playing boots and runners, an interstate travel allowance, income insurance, out-of-pocket medical expense coverage, and an allowance to pay for a carer for a child under 12 months of age when travelling interstate.
[src:2016-afl-women-s-draft/2017-afl-women-s-draft] It operated with players nominating for a single state's draft pool and players only being eligible to be drafted by clubs operating in that state.
[src:2016-afl-women-s-draft/2017-afl-women-s-draft] Clubs concluded the draft period with a total of 30 players, 27 of these being senior listed and three of these being rookie players.
[src:2016-afl-women-s-draft/2017-afl-women-s-draft] The rookie draft took place on 20 October 2017.
[src:2016-afl-women-s-draft/2017-afl-women-s-draft] Players qualify for the rookie draft if they are under the age of 21 or are crossing from another sport.
[src:2016-afl-women-s-draft/2017-afl-women-s-grand-final] The **2017 AFL Women's Grand Final** was an Australian rules football match held on 25 March 2017 to determine the premiers of the 2017 AFL Women's season, the league's inaugural season.
[src:2016-afl-women-s-draft/2017-afl-women-s-grand-final] Adelaide were victorious over minor premiers Brisbane, claiming the first AFL Women's premiership by a score of 35 points to 29.
[src:2016-afl-women-s-draft/2017-afl-women-s-grand-final] Brisbane had entered the grand final as undefeated, conceding only one draw during the season, while Adelaide conceded two losses, including a three-point loss to Brisbane in the fifth round.
[src:2016-afl-women-s-draft/2017-afl-women-s-grand-final] In the weeks prior to the match, concern centered around the venue of the match.
[src:2016-afl-women-s-draft/2017-afl-women-s-grand-final] Due to the venue's condition, the match was moved to Metricon Stadium, to act as a curtain-raiser to the round one "QClash" of the 2017 AFL season.
[src:2016-afl-women-s-draft/2017-afl-women-s-grand-final] The inaugural season of the AFL Women's competition, which featured eight teams, made use of a best-two qualification system straight through to the grand final, instead of a finals series system similar to the Australian Football League (AFL).
[src:2016-afl-women-s-draft/2017-afl-women-s-grand-final] The top two teams on the premiership ladder at the end of a seven-round home-and-away season would compete for the premiership in the grand final.
[src:2016-afl-women-s-draft/2017-afl-women-s-grand-final] The team that wins the minor premiership also wins the rights to host the match.
[src:2016-afl-women-s-draft/2017-afl-women-s-grand-final] The date of the match was set for 25 March, serving as a curtain-raiser match for the first round of the 2017 AFL season.
[src:2016-afl-women-s-draft/2017-afl-women-s-grand-final] The match was scheduled for an early afternoon start at 1:00 pm Australian Eastern Standard Time to boost attendance and television ratings, when no AFL matches were occurring—the first match of the day, a clash between Sydney and Port Adelaide, was scheduled for a 4:35 pm start time.
[src:2016-afl-women-s-draft/2017-afl-women-s-grand-final] Three days before the match, the starting time was changed to five minutes earlier (12:55 pm) due to the application of the heat policy, with the quarter and half-time breaks extended.
[src:2016-afl-women-s-draft/2017-afl-women-s-grand-final] Entering as wooden spoon favourites, Brisbane remained undefeated by the end of 2017 season, conceding only a draw with Carlton out of the season's seven games.
[src:2016-afl-women-s-draft/2017-afl-women-s-grand-final] After defeating the Western Bulldogs in round six and securing their sixth straight win, Brisbane mathematically qualified for a place in the 2017 AFL Women's Grand Final.
[src:2016-afl-women-s-draft/2017-afl-women-s-grand-final] After Adelaide, the second placed team, lost their sixth round match against Melbourne, Brisbane pulled away with two wins ahead of Adelaide at the beginning of the final round, securing the minor premiership and the right to host the grand final.
[src:2016-afl-women-s-draft/2017-afl-women-s-grand-final] For Melbourne to qualify for the grand final, they would have had to win their round seven match against Fremantle and due to Adelaide's advantage on points for/against, Adelaide would have had to lose their match against Collingwood.
[src:2016-afl-women-s-draft/2017-afl-women-s-grand-final] While Melbourne succeeded in defeating Fremantle by 54 points, the largest margin of the 2017 season, they were still behind Adelaide on point percentages.
[src:2016-afl-women-s-draft/2017-afl-women-s-grand-final] Adelaide secured their place in the grand final after a come-from-behind victory against Collingwood, noted for Sarah Perkins' four-goal performance.
[src:2016-afl-women-s-draft/2017-afl-women-s-grand-final] Both Adelaide and Melbourne finished the season with five wins and two losses, with Adelaide finishing with a 16.3 point percentage lead over Melbourne.
[src:2016-afl-women-s-draft/2017-afl-women-s-grand-final] The only match up between Adelaide and Brisbane before the grand final was Adelaide's 3-point loss to Brisbane in round five, which knocked Adelaide off the top of the ladder.
[src:2016-afl-women-s-draft/2017-afl-women-s-grand-final] After a higher-than-anticipated turnout to games in the first round of the season, capacity became an issue to AFL Women's organisers, who considered holding the grand final at the Melbourne Cricket Ground in the event that a Melbourne team became minor premiers.
[src:2016-afl-women-s-draft/2017-afl-women-s-grand-final] The match would then serve as a curtain-raiser match for the AFL round one match between Essendon and Hawthorn, to be held at the ground at 7:25 pm.
[src:2016-afl-women-s-draft/2017-afl-women-s-grand-final] Docklands Stadium was ruled out due to an AFL clash between St Kilda and Melbourne at the stadium occurring at 4:35 pm—considered by organisers as not enough time between matches.
[src:2016-afl-women-s-draft/2017-afl-women-s-grand-final] As the season progressed, the likelihood rose of the match not being held in Melbourne, as Brisbane and Adelaide performed well in the first few rounds.
[src:2016-afl-women-s-draft/2017-afl-women-s-grand-final] Adelaide Oval was pinned by AFL general manager of football operations Simon Lethlean as a venue for the match if Adelaide hosted it, though the team's losses in rounds five and six prevented it from happening.
[src:2016-afl-women-s-draft/2017-afl-women-s-grand-final] With Brisbane being favourites to host, the Gold Coast Football Club lobbied to hold the grand final at Metricon Stadium to prevent splitting crowds with the "QClash" match between Gold Coast and the Brisbane Lions being held on the same day at 6:25 pm, a plan backed by Lethlean.
[src:2016-afl-women-s-draft/2017-afl-women-s-grand-final] An alternative proposal, however, suggested the match be held at the Brisbane Lions' traditional home ground, the Gabba.
[src:2016-afl-women-s-draft/2017-afl-women-s-grand-final] After Brisbane became minor premiers and earned the right to host the grand final, concern for the Gabba's capability to host the match was raised.
[src:2016-afl-women-s-draft/2017-afl-women-s-grand-final] Floorboards installed at the venue for the Adele Live 2017 concerts in early March were originally due to be completely removed, and the pitch restored by 1 April, a week after the match.
[src:2016-afl-women-s-draft/2017-afl-women-s-grand-final] It would be great for Queensland football." The proposal was also supported by Queensland media, with some columnists such as Andrew Hamilton of *The Courier-Mail* criticising AFL Women's management for their organisation of the grand final.
[src:2016-afl-women-s-draft/2017-afl-women-s-grand-final] On 20 March, it was confirmed via a decision by the Department of National Parks, Sport and Racing that Metricon Stadium would host the match, to be played six hours prior to the QClash which takes place later the same evening at the venue.
[src:2016-afl-women-s-draft/2017-afl-women-s-grand-final] It was found that the Adele Live 2017 concert had damaged the turf at the Gabba, and that the ground's curator, Kevin Mitchell, had made the decision to replace the turf—a process which would not be finished in time for the grand final.
[src:2016-afl-women-s-draft/2017-afl-women-s-grand-final] While the decision was praised by the Gold Coast, both Brisbane and AFL management publicly expressed their dissatisfaction, putting the blame on Mitchell and the Gabba's management and ground curator.
[src:2016-afl-women-s-draft/2017-afl-women-s-grand-final] The club accused Mitchell of prioritising the 2017–18 Ashes series, claiming that the cricket pitch had already been sewn in advance of the series' first test, which would occur over seven months after the grand final.
[src:2016-afl-women-s-draft/2017-afl-women-s-grand-final] The teams were announced on 23 March, with both teams opting to go into the match unchanged from the final round of the home and away season.
[src:2016-afl-women-s-draft/2017-afl-women-s-grand-final] The 2017 AFL Women's Grand Final was broadcast on the Seven Network, as part of a broadcasting rights deal that saw Seven West Media gain broadcasting rights to all matches of the 2017 AFL Women's season, airing on the Seven Network, 7mate, or the video on demand service, PLUS7.
[src:2016-afl-women-s-draft/2017-afl-women-s-grand-final] Outside of Australia, it was made available live and for replay on the Watch AFL subscription web site and app.
[src:2016-afl-women-s-draft/2017-afl-women-s-rising-star] The AFL Women's Rising Star is an Australian rules football award given annually to the best young player in the AFL Women's (AFLW) for the year.
[src:2016-afl-women-s-draft/2017-afl-women-s-rising-star] Two eligible players are nominated each round of the home-and-away season; the players must have been under 21 at the beginning of the year and cannot have been previously nominated.
[src:2016-afl-women-s-draft/2017-afl-women-s-rising-star] Players suspended during the year cannot win.
[src:2016-afl-women-s-draft/2017-afl-women-s-rising-star] After the season's completion, an expert panel votes on the recipient.
[src:2016-afl-women-s-draft/2017-afl-women-s-rising-star] In 2016, National Australia Bank expanded its 14-year sponsorship of the Australian Football League (AFL) to the women's competition, including the naming rights to its Rising Star award, ahead of its first season in 2017.
[src:2016-afl-women-s-draft/2017-afl-women-s-rising-star] The inaugural Rising Star, who won $20,000, was announced at the AFLW's awards ceremony on 28 March, held at Peninsula, an event space in Docklands, Melbourne.
[src:2016-afl-women-s-draft/2017-afl-women-s-rising-star] The ceremony was live-streamed on the AFL's website and mobile app.
[src:2016-afl-women-s-draft/2017-afl-women-s-rising-star] The ten members of the year's voting panel were Mark Evans, Darren Flanigan, Ros Lanigan, Simon Lethlean, Jennie Loughnan, Peta Searle, Kevin Sheehan, Kelli Underwood, Josh Vanderloo and Shelley Ware.
[src:2016-afl-women-s-draft/2017-afl-women-s-rising-star] Ebony Marinoff of Adelaide was the inaugural winner, earning 47 votes.
[src:2016-afl-women-s-draft/2017-afl-women-s-rising-star] A midfielder, she led the league in tackles, laying a total of 70 for the season.
[src:2016-afl-women-s-draft/2017-afl-women-s-rising-star] She played in Adelaide's premiership side and was also named on the interchange bench in the season's AFLW All-Australian team.
[src:2016-afl-women-s-draft/2017-afl-women-s-rising-star] Melbourne amassed the most nominations during the season, with four players (Deanna Berry, Jasmine Grierson, Lily Mithen and Katherine Smith) selected.
